PRIMARY NAME: Elhassan Gaffar Mohammed DOB: 24 Jun 1952 Good quality a.k.a.: Gaffar Mohmed Elhassan Identification document: ID card No. 4302, Sudan (Ex-serviceman&amp;apos;s identification card) Justification: a) Major-General and Commander of the Western Military Region for the Sudanese Armed Forces (SAF). b) The Panel of Experts report that Major-General Gaffar Mohammed Elhassan stated to them that he had direct operational command (primarily tactical command) of all elements of the SAF in Darfur while he was in command of the Western Military Region. Elhassan held this position as Western Military Area Commander from Nov 2004 (approx.) to early 2006. The Panel&amp;apos;s information is that Elhassan was responsible for violations of paragraph 7 of SCR 1591 as by virtue of this position he requested (from Khartoum) and authorized (since 29 Mar 2005) the transfer of military equipment into Darfur without the prior approval of the 1591 Committee. Elhassan himself admitted to the Panel of Experts that aircraft, aircraft engines and other military equipment had been brought into Darfur from other parts of Sudan between 29 Mar 2005 and Dec 2005. For example he informed the Panel that 2 Mi-24 attack helicopters were brought unauthorized into Darfur between 18 and 21 Sep 2005. There are also reasonable grounds to believe that Elhassan was directly responsible, as Western Military Area Commander, for authorizing offensive military flights in the area around Abu Hamra, 23-24 Jul 2005 and in the Jebel Moon area of Western Darfur, on 19 Nov 2005. Mi-24 attack helicopters were involved in both operations and reportedly opened fire on both occasions. The Panel of Experts report that Elhassan indicated to the Panel that he himself approved requests for air support and other air operations in his capacity as Western Military Area Commander. (See Panel of Experts report, S/2006/65, paragraphs 266-269.) Through such actions Major-General Gaffar Mohammed Elhassan has breached relevant provisions of SCR 1591 and therefore meets the criteria to be designated by the Committee to be subjected to sanctions. PRIMARY NAME: Elhassan Gaffar Mohammed DOB: 24 Jun 1952 Good quality a.k.a.: Gaffar Mohmed Elhassan Identification document: ID card No. 4302, Sudan (Ex-serviceman&amp;apos;s identification card) Justification: a) Major-General and Commander of the Western Military Region for the Sudanese Armed Forces (SAF). b) The Panel of Experts report that Major-General Gaffar Mohammed Elhassan stated to them that he had direct operational command (primarily tactical command) of all elements of the SAF in Darfur while he was in command of the Western Military Region. Elhassan held this position as Western Military Area Commander from Nov 2004 (approx.) to early 2006. The Panel&amp;apos;s information is that Elhassan was responsible for violations of paragraph 7 of SCR 1591 as by virtue of this position he requested (from Khartoum) and authorized (since 29 Mar 2005) the transfer of military equipment into Darfur without the prior approval of the 1591 Committee. Elhassan himself admitted to the Panel of Experts that aircraft, aircraft engines and other military equipment had been brought into Darfur from other parts of Sudan between 29 Mar 2005 and Dec 2005. For example he informed the Panel that 2 Mi-24 attack helicopters were brought unauthorized into Darfur between 18 and 21 Sep 2005. There are also reasonable grounds to believe that Elhassan was directly responsible, as Western Military Area Commander, for authorizing offensive military flights in the area around Abu Hamra, 23-24 Jul 2005 and in the Jebel Moon area of Western Darfur, on 19 Nov 2005. Mi-24 attack helicopters were involved in both operations and reportedly opened fire on both occasions. The Panel of Experts report that Elhassan indicated to the Panel that he himself approved requests for air support and other air operations in his capacity as Western Military Area Commander. (See Panel of Experts report, S/2006/65, paragraphs 266-269.) Through such actions Major-General Gaffar Mohammed Elhassan has breached relevant provisions of SCR 1591 and therefore meets the criteria to be designated by the Committee to be subjected to sanctions. Other information: a) Retired from the Sudanese Army. b) Address: Resides in El Waha, Omdurman, Sudan. [UK SANCTIONS - UKHMT] (May 2006 - addition. Jul 2014 - amended). Appears on Interpol-United Nations Security Council Special Notice, subject to UN Sanctions - Al-Qaida and ISIL (Da&amp;apos;esh) (QDi.135). [BIOGRAPHY] Leader of the transnational organised crime syndicate known as the D-Company. 14 International warrants of arrest issued by the Government of India. Alleged terrorist. Beneficiary of United Arab Emirates based entities: Dolphin Management Services, Al-Dirham Currency Exchange, Almas Electronics, Yusuf Trading, Reem Yusuf Trading, Falaudi Trading Company, Gulf Coast Real Estates (reported Apr 2013).[IDENTIFICATION] Shaik Ibrahim (father) (deceased). Mushtaqeen Ibrahim (brother) (deceased). Anis Ibrahim Kaskar (brother). Iqbal Hasan Ibrahim (brother). Humayun Ibrahim (brother). Low Quality Alias: Hizarat. [FUNDING] Allegedly engaged in narcotics and arms trafficking, gambling, cricket match-fixing, prostitution, construction, real estate, hawala and the Bollywood film industry. Believed to operate businesses in Dubai, Pakistan and South Africa, notably shipping and trucking lines in Pakistan that smuggle arms into India and narcotics into Europe. Reportedly involved in the financing of terrorist groups such as Lashkar-e-Tayyiba (LeT) that carry out attacks in India. Possible ties to al-Qaida through shared trafficking routes. Reported to have assets in UK (USD450m) (reported Sep 2017). [REPORTS] 1986 - fled India to avoid criminal prosecution, first to Dubai, then to Karachi. Believed to be still in Pakistan. Charged, along with brother Anis Ibrahim, with masterminding the 1993 Mumbai bombings. 1993 - red notice arrest warrant issued by CBI. Wanted for trafficking gold and attacking customs officials with weapons. 2001 - suspected of instigating a series of bombings on the Mumbai Stock Exchange (Oct) and on the Indian Parliament (13 Dec). May 2005 - spouse and children applied for visas for a Commonwealth country, which does not have an extradition agreement with Pakistan. Status of request unknown (as of Nov 2006). Feb 2006 - non-bailable warrant of arrest issued by Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) under the Maharashtra Control of Organised Crime Act (MCOCA) relating to the alleged illegal importation of Gutkha manufacturing machinery to Pakistan. INR1.5m offered by CBI for information leading to arrest. 22 Jul 2006 - request for extradition to India rejected by Pakistan. Jan 2007 - reportedly sighted in Africa and the Middle East, notably in Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain, despite UN travel ban (2005). Feb 2007 - suspected involvement in cricket betting racket and match fixing in Nagpur, India involving Kamel Kishore Chadha and bookmaker Mukesh Kochkar. April 2008 - reported to be travelling on Mali passport. Aug 2008 - suspected to be funding terrorist activities of Students Islamic Movement of India (SIMI). Nov 2008 - suspected of involvement in the Mumbai terror attacks. Dec 2008 - reportedly figured in the list of 20 criminals wanted by India from Pakistan after the Mumbai terror attacks. Nov 2009 - figured in the World&amp;apos;s Most Powerful People list compiled by the Forbes magazine. May 2012 - reportedly owns 20 counterfeit passports. Jan 2013 - designated by the Israeli Ministerial Committee for National Security Affairs as a foreign terrorist. Jul 2013 - charge sheet filed by the Delhi Police in the Indian Premier League spot-fixing case. Charged for offences of cheating and conspiracy under Indian Penal Code and provisions of MCOCA. Oct 2017 - case registered for extortion (INR30m). Apr 2018 - properties to be seized by government as per Supreme Court order. Jun 2018 - charge sheet filed by Thane Police&amp;apos;s Anti-Extortion Cell for alleged extortion (INR30m). Inclusion in the category does not mean that an individual or entity is a terrorist or terrorist organisation or that they have any involvement in or connection to terrorism. [FUNDING] Allegedly engaged in narcotics and arms trafficking, gambling, cricket match-fixing, prostitution, construction, real estate, hawala and the Bollywood film industry. Believed to operate businesses in Dubai, Pakistan and South Africa, notably shipping and trucking lines in Pakistan that smuggle arms into India and narcotics into Europe. Reportedly involved in the financing of terrorist groups such as Lashkar-e-Tayyiba (LeT) that carry out attacks in India. Possible ties to al-Qaida through shared trafficking routes. Reported to have assets in UK (USD450m) (reported Sep 2017). [REPORTS] 1986 - fled India to avoid criminal prosecution, first to Dubai, then to Karachi. Believed to be still in Pakistan. Charged, along with brother Anis Ibrahim, with masterminding the 1993 Mumbai bombings. 1993 - red notice arrest warrant issued by CBI. Wanted for trafficking gold and attacking customs officials with weapons. 2001 - suspected of instigating a series of bombings on the Mumbai Stock Exchange (Oct) and on the Indian Parliament (13 Dec). April 2008 - reported to be travelling on Mali passport. Aug 2008 - suspected to be funding terrorist activities of Students Islamic Movement of India (SIMI). Nov 2008 - suspected of involvement in the Mumbai terror attacks. Dec 2008 - reportedly figured in the list of 20 criminals wanted by India from Pakistan after the Mumbai terror attacks. Nov 2009 - figured in the World&amp;apos;s Most Powerful People list compiled by the Forbes magazine. May 2012 - reportedly owns 20 counterfeit passports. Appears on Interpol-United Nations Security Council Special Notice, subject to UN Sanctions - Al-Qaida and ISIL (Da&amp;apos;esh) (QDi.067).[BIOGRAPHY] Alleged recruiter {Recruiting and Training} for al-Qaida in London. Radical Muslim cleric. Suspected to have been in contact with high-ranking Taliban and al-Qaida leaders. Detained (May 2004). [IDENTIFICATION] Nadjet Kamel Mostafa (spouse) (1984- ). Muhammad Mustapha Kamel (son). Hamza Mustafa Kamel (son). Imran Mostafa (son). Sufiyan Mustafa (son). Ola Kamal Mostafa (sister). Mohsin Ghalain (stepson). Studied civil engineering at Brighton Polytechnic. [FUNDING] Former imam at Finsbury Park mosque in north London. Purportedly worked as a doorman in London nightclub during studies and subsequently as a civil engineer. Reportedly collected unemployment paycheques from UK social welfare system. [REPORTS] 1979 - re-located from Egypt to UK. 1987 - believed to have met Abdullah Azzam in Makkah. Later worked in Jalalabad. Allegedly lost an eye and both hands on a de-mining project. 1993 - returned to the UK. 1995 - purportedly joined the mujahideen in Bosnia and Herzegovina. 1998 - suspected of facilitating the hostage-taking of 16 westerners by the Islamic Army of Aden in Yemen. 2000 - allegedly purchased property in Hammersmith, transferred to son Muhammad (Aug 2003). May 2004 - detained in UK. Warrant of extradition requested by US authorities. Held at Belmarsh High Security Prison. Oct 2004 - faced terrorism charges in UK. US extradition proceedings postponed. Jan 2006 - trial commenced at the Old Bailey, London. Charged with a number of offences committed prior to 2004. Denied charges. Feb 2006 - convicted on charges of soliciting to murder, inciting racial hatred, and possession of a document deemed useful to terrorists. Sentenced to 7 years imprisonment. Oct 2006 - appealed sentence. Nov 2006 - appeal rejected and conviction upheld. Jan 2007 - ruled to be liable for more than GBP1m of legal aid. Seizure of assets permitted by UK judge to recover legal costs. May 2007 - extradition hearing commenced on US allegations of attempting to establish a terrorist training camp in Oregon, hostage-taking in Yemen, facilitating terrorist training in Afghanistan, and conspiracy to wage terrorist attacks against the West. Nov 2007 - extradition to USA approved by UK court. Mar 2008 - in custody in UK. Jun 2008 - extradition to USA approved by UK High Court. Aug 2008 - interim order blocking extradition to USA granted by the European Court of Human Rights (ECHR). Jul 2010 - extradition process halted by ECHR. Nov 2010 - UK citizenship restored by court. Apr 2012 - extradition to USA approved by ECHR. Jul 2012 - appeal filed to ECHR over extradition to USA. Sep 2012 - appeal rejected. Oct 2012 - extradited to USA. Reportedly on trial. Sep 2013 - request to dismiss terrorism charges denied by US federal judge. Trial date set to Mar 2014. Nov 2013 - trial date moved to April 2014. Apr 2014 - on trial in New York. May 2014 - found guilty of 11 terrorism charges. Jan 2015 - sentenced to life imprisonment. Aug 2018 - no further information reported.[TERRORISM CATEGORY NOTICE] This category includes information about individuals who have reportedly been arrested or charged on suspicion of involvement in terrorism or terror related activities and those convicted of any terror related crime. The category also includes individuals or entities identified on national or internationally recognised banning, warning or wanted lists as connected to terrorism or individuals who are reportedly connected to a terrorist organisation that is included on any national or international list. Inclusion in the category does not mean that an individual or entity is a terrorist or terrorist organisation or that they have any involvement in or connection to terrorism. Individuals included in this category may not have been convicted of any terror related crime or, where convicted, may appeal such conviction; you should review the content carefully and in accordance with our terms and conditions, further enquiries should be made of the report subject to investigate the outcome of any alleged arrest, charges or conviction or any reported suspected involvement in any terror related activity and whether such allegations are denied.
